<subSubSection id="C331C195B743FFFDFD66FC9FFD92F2A9" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8B94921EB743FFFDFD66FC9FFB9BF5CA" blockId="4.[717,1314,804,1231]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="B95F4E0CB743FFFDFD66FC9FFCA2F51B" bold="true" box="[717,873,804,837]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB743FFFDFCD3FC9FFC35F532" authority="Hewitt, 1927" authorityName="Hewitt" authorityYear="1927" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Pronolagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="crassicaudatus" subSpecies="saundersiae">Pronolagus crassicaudatus saundersiae Hewitt, 1927</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation id="3B439843B743FFFDFBB5FCF4FB9BF5CA" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3805018318" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">“Albany District,” Eastern Cape, South Africa.</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B94921EB743FFFDFD64FC19FD92F2A9" blockId="4.[717,1314,804,1231]" lastBlockId="4.[107,1313,1238,2416]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
Initially, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB743FFFDFCFEFC19FBDCF5E5" authorityName="Hewitt" authorityYear="1927" box="[853,1047,930,955]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Pronolagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="saundersiae">P. saundersiae</taxonomicName>
was included as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB743FFFDFC67FC71FB79F5BD" baseAuthorityName="I. Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[972,1202,970,995]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Pronolagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crassicaudatus">P crassicaudatus</taxonomicName>
. Later, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB743FFFDFD64FC52FC46F254" authorityName="Hewitt" authorityYear="1927" box="[719,909,1001,1034]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Pronolagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="saundersiae">P. saundersiae</taxonomicName>
was included as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB743FFFDFC9FFBABFC09F26F" baseAuthorityName="A. Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[820,962,1040,1073]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Pronolagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rupestris">P. rupestris</taxonomicName>
but now has species status. Distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB743FFFDFC4EFB87FB57F207" authorityName="Hewitt" authorityYear="1927" box="[997,1180,1084,1113]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Pronolagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="saundersiae">P. saundersiae</taxonomicName>
does not overlap that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB743FFFDFC01FBDCFBFDF2DE" baseAuthorityName="A. Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[938,1078,1127,1152]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Pronolagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rupestris">P. rupestris</taxonomicName>
, but the eastern part of its distribution overlaps that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB743FFFDFD64FB09FC7CF291" baseAuthorityName="I. Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[719,951,1202,1231]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Pronolagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crassicaudatus">P crassicaudatus</taxonomicName>
and the north-western part that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB743FFFDFEB8FB6DFE66F2A9" authorityName="Jameson" authorityYear="1907" box="[275,429,1238,1271]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Pronolagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="randensis">P. randensis</taxonomicName>
. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C331C195B743FFFDFFC0FB46FB35F318" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" type="distribution">
<caption id="DF54C296B743FFFDFFC0FB46FB35F318" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6625553" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6625553" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6625553/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" targetBox="[104,694,812,1225]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph id="8B94921EB743FFFDFFC0FB46FB35F318" blockId="4.[107,1313,1238,2416]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="B95F4E0CB743FFFDFFC0FB46FED0F340" bold="true" box="[107,283,1277,1310]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Distribution.</emphasis>
S &amp; E South Africa (Western, Northern and Eastern Cape, Free State, KwaZulu-Natal, Limpopo, and Mpumalanga provinces), Lesotho, and W Swaziland.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C331C195B743FFFDFFC0FAEEFE8DF0DF" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B94921EB743FFFDFFC0FAEEFE8DF0DF" blockId="4.[107,1313,1238,2416]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="B95F4E0CB743FFFDFFC0FAEEFEBDF330" bold="true" box="[107,374,1365,1390]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 380-540 mm, tail 50-115 mm, ear 80-110 mm, hindfoot 85-100 mm; weight 1.4-2.1 kg. Hewitt’s Red Rock Hare is medium-sized and has thick, dense, woolly fur. Dorsal pelage is grizzled brown anteriorly, rufous posteriorly, and bright rufous on rump. Flanks are pale, and ventral fur is pale rufous to whitish rufous. Head and ears are grayish brown, and cheeks are grayish white. Throat patch is brownish, and nuchal patch is rufous. Forelimbs are bright rufous, and hindlimbs are pale rufous. Tail is red or pale sandy. Fur color varies geographically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C331C195B743FFFDFFC7F93CFF0DF119" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B94921EB743FFFDFFC7F93CFF0DF119" blockId="4.[107,1313,1238,2416]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="B95F4E0CB743FFFDFFC7F93CFF10F0F6" bold="true" box="[108,219,1671,1704]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Habitat.</emphasis>
Solid rocks (“kopjes”) and rocky hillsides with boulders, where grassy or scrubby vegetation occurs. Rock crevices and boulders are essential habitat features, and gaps between them naturally fragment populations. Hewitt’s Red Rock Hare is generally found at higher elevations than Smith’s Red Rock Hare (
<taxonomicName id="4C2BE99DB743FFFDFBA2F946FB5EF140" baseAuthorityName="A. Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[1033,1173,1789,1822]" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Pronolagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rupestris">P. rupestris</taxonomicName>
) in South Africa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
